Drop redundant mingw-w64 strip on host-arch restore_signature binary.

The nanodump Makefile builds scripts/restore_signature with the host gcc
(line 78) and then strips it with x86_64-w64-mingw32-strip (line 79).
The Windows cross-strip happens to accept x86_64 ELF as a side effect of
binutils' BFD library, so the bug is invisible on amd64 hosts. On arm64
hosts gcc produces aarch64 ELF, which mingw-w64-strip can't recognize,
breaking the build.

The strip is also redundant: line 78's `-s` flag already strips at link.

diff --git a/Creds-BOF/nanodump/Makefile b/Creds-BOF/nanodump/Makefile
--- a/Creds-BOF/nanodump/Makefile
+++ b/Creds-BOF/nanodump/Makefile
@@ -76,7 +76,6 @@ nanodump:
 	@$(STRIP_x64) --strip-unneeded dist/$(BOFNAME)_ppl_medic.x64.o && echo '[+] nanodump_ppl_medic x64' || echo '[!] nanodump_ppl_medic x64'

 	@$(GCC) source/restore_signature.c -o scripts/restore_signature -static -s -Os
-	@$(STRIP_x64) --strip-all scripts/restore_signature

 clean:
 	@rm -f dist/*
